# Rancher Instance

- The environment variables can be accessed via .env
- It can be accessed at https://$RANCHER_HOST_NAME
- You can use the following admin credentials
- user: $RANCHER_ADMIN_USER
- pass: $RANCHER_ADMIN_PASS

# Two URLs: stock Rancher vs your dev server (read before driving the browser)

There are two different web endpoints in this project and they are NOT interchangeable. Driving the wrong
one is the most common way to waste a verification run, because your code changes only exist in one of them.

- **Stock Rancher** - `https://$RANCHER_HOST_NAME` (also reachable at `https://localhost:8443`).
  The real Rancher server: the API backend AND the unmodified, upstream dashboard UI it ships with. It does
  NOT contain your local code changes. Use it to reproduce the original bug, to create supporting resources,
  and for any API calls.
- **Dev server** - `https://localhost:8005`. The dashboard built from `/workspace/dashboard` with your local
  changes, served by `yarn dev`. This is the ONLY place your fix is visible. Use it to verify a fix and to
  record or screenshot the after-fix state.

Important details about the dev server:
- It is NOT started automatically. Start it yourself, e.g. `cd /workspace/dashboard && yarn dev` (the `API`
  env var is already exported to the stock Rancher backend, so auth and API calls proxy there).
- `wait-for-sidecars` does NOT wait for it - it only checks CDP and the Rancher API. After starting `yarn dev`,
  poll the dev server (`curl -sk https://localhost:8005`) until it serves the compiled app, then drive the
  browser. The first compile takes a while.
- Log in on the dev server with the same admin credentials above.

Rule of thumb: reproduce + setup -> stock Rancher; verify the fix + after-fix media -> dev server (8005).
